<h3 id="symmetric-groups">Symmetric groups</h3>

<h4 id="notation">Notation</h4>
<ol>
  <li>$S_n$: Group of permutations on a set with n elements.
    <ul>
      <li>$S_3$: group of puermutations on a set with 3 elements, and it has $3!$ elements</li>
      <li>$S_4$: permutations of ${1,2,3,4}$, and it has $4!$ elements</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>

<h4 id="what-good-will-this-do-me">What good will this do me?</h4>
<ol>
  <li>Every finite group is a subgroup of symmetric group.</li>
</ol>

<h3 id="alternating-groups">Alternating groups</h3>

<h4 id="definition">Definition</h4>
<ol>
  <li>Alternating groups: One of the most important subgroups of $S_n$ is the set of all even
permutations, $A_n$. The group $A_n$ is called the $\textbf{alternating group on}$ 
n $\textbf{letters}$.</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="theorem">Theorem</h4>
<ol>
  <li>The set $A_n$ is a subgroup of $S_n$</li>
  <li>The number of even permutations in $S_n$, $n \geq 2 $, is equal to the
number of odd permuations; hence the order of $A_n$ is $\frac{n!}{2}$</li>
</ol>

